* We=E2=80=99re no longer advertising with you=E2=80=A6 and you=E2=80=99re =
also not invited: The balance of power between fashion magazines and brands=
 shifted dramatically post-2008, as companies pulled their advertising doll=
ars out
of traditional media and poured them into celebrity ambassadorships and dir=
ect channels=E2=80=94environments where they didn=E2=80=99t have to cater f=
or fashion credits. More than 15 years later, magazines have never been mor=
e desperate, and fashion brands have never been in more control. These days=
, the dynamic is particularly dire because most brands are underperforming =
and slashing advertising budgets. Magazine editors and publishers have to o=
ffer more to persuade them to stay=E2=80=94i.e., give them more
editorial control, cheaper rates, or both. It=E2=80=99s a dismal state of a=
ffairs.

From what I gathered in Milan, the books with proven luxury consumers are s=
urviving=E2=80=94perhaps justified as brand marketing channels=E2=80=94whil=
e everyone else is getting iced out. And here=E2=80=99s a deeper wrinkle: M=
any brands this season are choosing to stage extremely small shows, which m=
eans invite lists have been reduced significantly. Louis Vuitton, which typ=
ically invites more than 1,000 people to its show, will usher in
around 300 next Monday. The Tom Ford and Givenchy shows=E2=80=94the latter =
of which is taking place in their offices=E2=80=94are also small. Many prom=
inent editors will get left out.

